structive policy responses requires an understanding of how and the extent to which freshwater supplies and nutrition jointly influences health outcomes the proposed project which involves both place based empirical research and analysis of secondary data will explore these water nutrition health interconnections it will identify the extent which and potential causal mechanisms by which access to domestic and productive water supplies and associated nutritional benefits affect the progression of both hiv and tb among adults living in rural african households additional information on other of davis water and development projects downloads pdf+ research plan modified june 2011 pdf evp water health food2011_web pdf 119.1 kb contact jenna davis funding provided by environmental venture projects woods institute for the environment global underdevelopment action fund freeman spogli institute for international studies publications cover freshwater availability and water fetching distance affect child health in sub saharan africa amy pickering jenna davis environmental science and technology vol 46 4 2012 html+ search fsi search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages research news in sub saharan africa a shorter walk to water saves lives march 5 2012 fse fsi stanford news new environmental venture grants fsi stanford fse reap in the news the stanford report on june 24 2011 support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4581 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
